We employed SDG scores of 31 provinces in China (excluding Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan) evaluated by Xu et al. (2020) (Fig. 1
                        ). The assessment of chosen SDG scores employed 119 targets that belongs to 17 SDGs. In particular, Xu et al. (2020) constructed 55 new targets for environmental and social evaluations and also utilized some indicators from the SDG Index Monitoring Framework and Dashboards report. The data sources selected include China's 19 statistical yearbooks, national census, and national people's congress reports. Throughout the evaluation of data uncertainty, sensitivity, and availability, the chosen data is more accurate and comprehensive than other SDG data (Jeffrey Sachs et al., 2018). Following Rockström and Sukhdev (2016), SDGs were divided into four categories, i.e., environment, society, economy, and management (Table 1
                        ). Notably, SDG 7 (affordable and clean energy) was divided into the economic category based on the research conducted by D'Adamo et al. (2022) and Fuso Nerini et al. (2018).

In this study, synergies and trade-offs were used to explore how land-use efficiency impacts SDG practice. Positive (e.g., LCRPGR, LCR, or PGR were conducive to SDG progress) and negative correlations (e.g., LCRPGR, LCR, or PGR hindered SDG progress) were utilized to represent synergy and trade-off. We chose nonparametric Spearman's rank correlation (

                                 ρ

                           ) to determine the synergy or trade-off between LCRPGR, LCR, and PGR and SDGs 1–17 (Pradhan et al., 2017).
